article.headline: Missouri 85, Stephen F. Austin 56
article.story: For the Associated Press COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- The key to staying off the bench and on the floor, Kalen Grimes said, is to rebound and not turn the ball over. In Missouri's 85-56 win over Stephen F. Austin Saturday, the 6-foot-9 St. Louis native did that, and led Missouri with 14 points and nine rebounds in 20 minutes. It was something he wasn't able to do in Sunday's 81-75 win over Davidson, in which he scored just two points and committed three turnovers in nine minutes. "If you rebound, offense will come," Grimes said. "I was just trying to grab what I could." Against the Lumberjacks, Missouri Coach Mike Anderson said his junior forward looked more relaxed, which was evident from the start. Grimes scored Missouri's first two baskets and established a dominance in the paint as the Tigers (6-0) jumped out to an 8-0 run. With the help of Grimes and Leo Lyons, who is becoming one of Missouris most consistent reserves, Missouri outscored the Lumberjacks 48-14 in the paint. A lot of those scores came during a 14-2 run to end the first half, which gave the Tigers a 32-17 lead at the break, and a 9-0 run to start the second to put the game out of reach. "We had a tough time tonight with their ball pressure," Stephen F. Austin Coach Danny Kaspar said. "That kind of took the wind out of us." Stephen F. Austin (2-3) entered the game with what appeared to be a threatening force to Missouri's inside game. Matt Kingsley, 6-foot-9, led the Lumberjacks in scoring with 15.8 points and six rebounds while 6-foot-6, 255 pound Antuane Miller averaged 12.5 points and 6.5 rebounds off the bench. But Grimes and Lyons were able to shut down one of them. Miller led Stephen F. Austin with 21 points, but Kingsley scored just three points in seven minutes. The two combined for eight rebounds. To complement Grimes solid game, in which he shot 6-for-7 from the field, Lyons scored nine points on 4-for-5 shooting and pulled down six rebounds. "Our main focus was to rebound, go in and stop him," Lyons said. "It showed in the numbers, on the rebounds, what we were trying to do." Like in the Tigers' previous games, they were able to build leads with their pressure defense. The Tigers, who entered the game ranked ninth nationally with 56 steals and 11th nationally with 111 forced turnovers, made 13 steals and forced 27 turnovers. Junior college transfer Stefhon Hannah scored just two points on 1-for-6 shooting in the first half, but he contributed in other ways, Anderson said. His behind-the-back pass to Marshall Brown just four minutes into the game ignited the season-high crowd of 7,470, gave Missouri an 8-0 lead and prompted a Stephen F. Austin timeout. Hannah made all four of his shots from the field in the second half to finish with 12 points, seven steals and nine assists, which ties his season high. "He gives that aggressiveness that you have to have when you play this particular type of basketball," Anderson said. "He plays to win, thats the best way to describe him." Anderson was also pleased with the play of his bench. Two games after scoring 49 points with in an 89-69 win over Lipscomb, Missouri's reserves scored 40 points and grabbed 14 rebounds. Freshman Keon Lawrence led the reserves with 11 points on 5-for-8 shooting and three other players scored at least five points. In all, 12 different Missouri players scored. "With our team, weve got like all types of scorers," Hannah said, "so its going to be a different person every night. We just play, we just play hard."
